{"title_page": "Napaimute, Alaska", "text_new": "{{Lead too short|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Napaimute\n|official_name            = \n|settlement_type          = [[Unincorporated area|Unincorporated community]]  \n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = \n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|pushpin_map              = USA Alaska\n|pushpin_label_position   = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location within the state of Alaska\n|pushpin_mapsize          = \n|image_map                = \n|map_caption              = Location within Bethel census area\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Alaska]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of census areas in Alaska|Census&nbsp;area]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Bethel Census Area, Alaska|Bethel]]\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = [[Alaska Senate|State senator]]\n|leader_name              = [[Lyman Hoffman]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\n|leader_title1            = [[Alaska House of Representatives|State rep.]]\n|leader_name1             = [[Zach Fansler]] (D)\n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = \n|area_land_km2            = \n|area_water_km2           =\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[United States Census, 2010|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 2\n|population_density_km2   = auto\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[Alaska Time Zone|Alaska (AKST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -9\n|timezone_DST             = AKDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -8\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_ft             = \n|coordinates              = {{coord|61|27|43|N|158|38|21|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]s\n|postal_code              = \n|area_code                = \n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = \n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 2418727<ref>{{gnis|2418727}}</ref>\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n}}\n\n'''Napaimute''' ({{lang-esu|Napamiut}}) is an [[unincorporated area|unincorporated]] [[Alaska Native]] village located in the [[Bethel Census Area, Alaska|Bethel Census Area]] of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Alaska]]. It is classified as an Alaskan Native Village Statistical Area. As of the 2010 U.S. Census, it has a population of 2. This is up from a population of zero in 2000.\n\n==History==\n{{unreferenced section|date=February 2018}}\nEnglishman George Hoffman established a trading post at the location of present-day Napaimute in 1906. The village that formed around the trading post was called Hoffman's. The middle Kuskokwim Valley was seeing and influx of gold prospectors at that time and Hoffman's became an important supply and trade center. George Hoffman would soon relocated to [[Georgetown, Alaska|Georgetown]], and the name of the village was changed to Napaimute. In [[Yup'ik language]], the word Napaimute translates to \"forest people\". The first territorial school along the Kuskokwim River was built in 1920 at Napaimute. By 1930, the US census was reporting a Napaimute population of 111, however, the population then began to decline, and by 1969, the village's last permanent resident had left the village. With the passage of the [[Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act]] in 1971, a village corporation called Napaimute Limited was formed and in 1975, one of its members established permanent residency at the village. the village council was able to receive federal recognition as an [[Alaska Native Tribe]] in 1994, which enabled it to start receiving funding from the [[Bureau of Indian Affairs]]. Current efforts to revitalize the community are evident by the set up of a sawmill in 2001, tribal operations in 2002, and an airport feasibility study launched in 2004.\n\n==Geography==\nGeorgetown is located at {{coord|61|32|N|158|40|W|region:US_type:city}} on the north bank of the upper [[Kuskokwim River]] 28 miles east of [[Aniak, Alaska|Aniak]] in the Kilbuck-Kuskokwim mountains. Napaimute is accessible by boat, or snowmobile (winter).\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1880= 60\n|1890= 23\n|1930= 111\n|1940= 75\n|1950= 44\n|1980= 4\n|1990= 3\n|2000= 0\n|2010= 2\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 6, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\nNapaimute first appeared on the 1880 U.S. Census as an unincorporated [[Tinneh]] village of 60 residents (all Tinneh).<ref>http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/1880a_v1-17.pdf</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://books.google.com/?id=Rr9RAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA49&lpg=PA49&dq=%22Agaligamute%22#v=onepage&q=napaimiut&f=false | title=Geological Survey Professional Paper| year=1949}}</ref> In 1890, it returned as \"Napaimiut\" (all 23 residents were Native).<ref>http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/1890a_v8-01.pdf</ref> It did not return again until 1930, this time as \"Napaimut.\" In 1940, it returned as \"Napamiute.\" In 1950, it returned under its 1890 census name, \"Napaimiut.\" It did not return again until 1980, when it returned as its original 1880 name and spelling, Napaimute. It was classified as an unincorporated Alaskan Native Village Statistical Area (ANVSA) in each successive census.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bethel Census Area, Alaska}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.napaimute.org Native Village of Napaimute]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Bethel Census Area, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Unorganized Borough, Alaska]]\n", "text_old": "{{Lead too short|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Napaimute\n|official_name            = \n|settlement_type          = [[Unincorporated area|Unincorporated community]]  \n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = \n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|pushpin_map              = USA Alaska\n|pushpin_label_position   = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location within the state of Alaska\n|pushpin_mapsize          = \n|image_map                = \n|map_caption              = Location within Bethel census area\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Alaska]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of census areas in Alaska|Census&nbsp;area]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Bethel Census Area, Alaska|Bethel]]\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = [[Alaska Senate|State senator]]\n|leader_name              = [[Lyman Hoffman]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\n|leader_title1            = [[Alaska House of Representatives|State rep.]]\n|leader_name1             = [[Zach Fansler]] (D)\n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = \n|area_land_km2            = \n|area_water_km2           =\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[United States Census, 2010|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 2\n|population_density_km2   = auto\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[Alaska Time Zone|Alaska (AKST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -9\n|timezone_DST             = AKDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -8\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_ft             = \n|coordinates              = {{coord|61|27|43|N|158|38|21|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]s\n|postal_code              = \n|area_code                = \n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = \n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 2418727<ref>{{gnis|2418727}}</ref>\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n}}\n\n'''Napaimute''' (''Napamiut'' in [[Yup'ik language|Yup'ik]]) is an [[unincorporated area|unincorporated]] [[Alaska Native]] village located in the [[Bethel Census Area, Alaska|Bethel Census Area]] of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Alaska]]. It is classified as an Alaskan Native Village Statistical Area. As of the 2010 U.S. Census, it has a population of 2. This is up from a population of zero in 2000.\n\n==History==\n{{unreferenced section|date=February 2018}}\nEnglishman George Hoffman established a trading post at the location of present-day Napaimute in 1906. The village that formed around the trading post was called Hoffman's. The middle Kuskokwim Valley was seeing and influx of gold prospectors at that time and Hoffman's became an important supply and trade center. George Hoffman would soon relocated to [[Georgetown, Alaska|Georgetown]], and the name of the village was changed to Napaimute. In [[Yup'ik language]], the word Napaimute translates to \"forest people\". The first territorial school along the Kuskokwim River was built in 1920 at Napaimute. By 1930, the US census was reporting a Napaimute population of 111, however, the population then began to decline, and by 1969, the village's last permanent resident had left the village. With the passage of the [[Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act]] in 1971, a village corporation called Napaimute Limited was formed and in 1975, one of its members established permanent residency at the village. the village council was able to receive federal recognition as an [[Alaska Native Tribe]] in 1994, which enabled it to start receiving funding from the [[Bureau of Indian Affairs]]. Current efforts to revitalize the community are evident by the set up of a sawmill in 2001, tribal operations in 2002, and an airport feasibility study launched in 2004.\n\n==Geography==\nGeorgetown is located at {{coord|61|32|N|158|40|W|region:US_type:city}} on the north bank of the upper [[Kuskokwim River]] 28 miles east of [[Aniak, Alaska|Aniak]] in the Kilbuck-Kuskokwim mountains. Napaimute is accessible by boat, or snowmobile (winter).\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1880= 60\n|1890= 23\n|1930= 111\n|1940= 75\n|1950= 44\n|1980= 4\n|1990= 3\n|2000= 0\n|2010= 2\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 6, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\nNapaimute first appeared on the 1880 U.S. Census as an unincorporated [[Tinneh]] village of 60 residents (all Tinneh).<ref>http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/1880a_v1-17.pdf</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://books.google.com/?id=Rr9RAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA49&lpg=PA49&dq=%22Agaligamute%22#v=onepage&q=napaimiut&f=false | title=Geological Survey Professional Paper| year=1949}}</ref> In 1890, it returned as \"Napaimiut\" (all 23 residents were Native).<ref>http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/1890a_v8-01.pdf</ref> It did not return again until 1930, this time as \"Napaimut.\" In 1940, it returned as \"Napamiute.\" In 1950, it returned under its 1890 census name, \"Napaimiut.\" It did not return again until 1980, when it returned as its original 1880 name and spelling, Napaimute. It was classified as an unincorporated Alaskan Native Village Statistical Area (ANVSA) in each successive census.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bethel Census Area, Alaska}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.napaimute.org Native Village of Napaimute]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Bethel Census Area, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Unorganized Borough, Alaska]]\n", "name_user": "Menchi", "label": "safe", "comment": "langtags", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Napaimute,_Alaska"}
{"title_page": "Kasigluk, Alaska", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name                   = Kasigluk\n| native_name                     = Kassigluq\n      | native_name_lang = esu \n| motto                           = \n| settlement_type                 = [[Census-designated place]]\n| nickname                        = <!-- Images -->\n| image_skyline                   = Z09-a.jpg\n| imagesize                       = \n| image_caption                   = Aerial photograph of Kasigluk\n| image_flag                      = \n| image_seal                      = <!-- Maps -->\n| image_map                       = AKMap-doton-Atmautluak.PNG\n| mapsize                         = 250px\n| map_caption                     = Location of Kasigluk, Alaska\n| image_map1                      = \n| mapsize1                        = \n| map_caption1                    = <!-- Location -->\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = United States\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Alaska]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of boroughs and census areas in Alaska|Census Area]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Bethel Census Area, Alaska|Bethel]]\n| government_footnotes            = \n| government_type                 = \n| leader_title                    = [[Alaska Senate|State senator]]\n| leader_name                     = [[Lyman Hoffman]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D-C]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alaskasenate.org/2020/member/lyman-hoffman/ |title=Senator Lyman Hoffman |publisher=Alaskasenate.org |website=Alaska Senate Majority |access-date=November 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| leader_title1                   = [[Alaska House of Representatives|State rep.]]\n| leader_name1                    = [[Tiffany Zulkosky]] (D)\n| established_title               = \n| established_date                = <!-- Area -->\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_magnitude                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = 34.0\n| area_land_km2                   = 31.3\n| area_water_km2                  = 2.7\n| area_total_sq_mi                = \n| area_land_sq_mi                 = \n| area_water_sq_mi                = <!-- Population -->\n| population_as_of                = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_total                = 569\n| population_density_km2          = 18.2\n| population_density_sq_mi        = <!-- General information -->\n| timezone                        = [[Alaska Time Zone|Alaska (AKST)]]\n| utc_offset                      = -9\n| timezone_DST                    = AKDT\n| utc_offset_DST                  = -8\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| elevation_ft                    = \n| coordinates                     = {{coord|60|53|31|N|162|32|9|W|region:US-AK|display=inline}}\n| postal_code_type                = [[ZIP code]]\n| postal_code                     = 99609\n| area_code                       = [[Area code 907|907]]\n| blank_name                      = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info                      = 02-37975\n| blank1_name                     = \n| blank1_info                     = \n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = \n| name                            = \n}}\n[[File:Russian orthodox church in Kasigluk.jpg|thumb|Holy Trinity Russian Orthodox Church]]\n'''Kasigluk''' {{IPAc-en|k|\u0259|\u02c8|s|\u026a|\u0261|l|\u028a|k}} ({{lang-esu|Kassigluq}}) is a [[census-designated place]] (CDP) in the [[Bethel Census Area, Alaska|Bethel Census Area]] in the U.S. state of [[Alaska]]. At the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]] the population was 569,<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US0237975| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212182811/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US0237975| url-status=dead| archive-date=February 12, 2020| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): Kasigluk CDP, Alaska| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> up from 543 in 2000. Kasigluk consists of two smaller villages, called Akiuk and Akula.\n\n==Geography==\nKasigluk is located at {{coord|60|53|31|N|162|32|9|W|type:city}} (60.892005, -162.535805)<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> along the Johnson River in the [[Yukon\u2013Kuskokwim Delta]] of western Alaska. It is approximately {{convert|20|mi}} northwest of [[Bethel, Alaska|Bethel]].\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the CDP has a total area of {{convert|34.0|km2|disp=flip}}, of which {{convert|31.3|km2|disp=flip}} is land and {{convert|2.7|km2|disp=flip}}, or 7.94%, is water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1940= 66\n|1950= 111\n|1960= 244\n|1990= 425\n|2000= 543\n|2010= 569\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 6, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\nKasigluk first appeared on the 1940 U.S. Census as an unincorporated native village named \"Kaseglok.\" In 1950 and 1960, it appeared as \"Kasiglook.\" In 1969, Kasigluk and a nearby village of [[Nunapitchuk, Alaska|Nunapitchuk]] merged to form the city of [[Akolmiut, Alaska|Akolmiut]]. The combined population in 1970 was 526 and in 1980 was 641. In 1982, both communities decided to dissolve Akolmiut and become separate cities again. 1990 was the first census where Kasigluk appeared with its present spelling. In 1996, Kasigluk disincorporated and was made a census-designated place effective with the 2000 census.\n\nAs of the census<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 543 people, 101 households, and 91 families residing in the CDP.  The population density was 44.5 people per square mile (17.2/km\u00b2).  There were 110 housing units at an average density of 9.0/sq&nbsp;mi (3.5/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the CDP was 3.31% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 96.50% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], and 0.18% from two or more races.  0.37% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 101 households out of which 72.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 67.3% were married couples living together, 15.8% had a female householder with no husband present, and 9.9% were non-families. 9.9% of all households were made up of individuals and 1.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 5.38 and the average family size was 5.81.\n\nIn the CDP, the population was spread out with 46.6% under the age of 18, 9.6% from 18 to 24, 26.3% from 25 to 44, 11.8% from 45 to 64, and 5.7% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 21 years. For every 100 females, there were 98.9 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 98.6 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the CDP was $31,500, and the median income for a family was $33,750. Males had a median income of $16,667 versus $18,750 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the CDP was $7,194.  About 18.9% of families and 22.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 26.7% of those under age 18 and none of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Wind power==\nRural Alaska villages have traditionally relied upon [[diesel generator]]s for their electrical needs. Kasigluk is one of several rural Alaska villages implementing [[wind power]]; they have three turbines, each with a capacity of 100 [[kilowatt]]s.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.nativeenergy.com/projects.html#8| title=Our Featured Projects| publisher=Native Energy| accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| url=http://tdworld.com/info_systems/highlights/Alaskan-Electric-Wind/| title=Alaskan Electric Cooperative Expands Wind Turbine Fleet| publisher=T&D World Magazine| date=Nov 5, 2005| accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> With fuel costs rising as high as $6 per gallon in mid-2005, wind power is being pursued not only for ecological reasons, but also to reduce the cost of living in impoverished communities such as Kasigluk.\n\n==Education==\nThe village has two schools operated by the [[Lower Kuskokwim School District]]:\n* Kasigluk-Akula Elitnaurvik School\n** The school covers PreK-12 and is a bilingual English-[[Yugtun language|Yugtun]] school. {{Asof|2018}} it has about 120 students.<ref>\"[http://akula.lksd.org/about/akula_school Akula School].\" Kasigluk-Akula Elitnaurvik School. Retrieved on July 13, 2018.</ref>\n* Kasigluk Akiuk Memorial School\n** The school covers PreK-12. {{Asof|2018}} it has about 100 students.<ref>\"[http://akiuk.lksd.org/about/akiuk_memorial_school Akiuk Memorial School].\" Kasigluk Akiuk Memorial School. Retrieved on July 13, 2018.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070311015559/http://www.lknea.org/siteinfo/akiuk.htm Lower Kuskokwim School District - Kasigluk-Akiuk]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070311015608/http://www.lknea.org/siteinfo/akula.htm Lower Kuskokwim School District - Kasigluk-Akula]\n\n{{Coord|display=title|60.892005|-162.535805}}\n{{Bethel Census Area, Alaska}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Former cities in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Bethel Census Area, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Unorganized Borough, Alaska]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name                   = Kasigluk\n| native_name                     = Kassigluq\n| motto                           = \n| settlement_type                 = [[Census-designated place]]\n| nickname                        = <!-- Images -->\n| image_skyline                   = Z09-a.jpg\n| imagesize                       = \n| image_caption                   = Aerial photograph of Kasigluk\n| image_flag                      = \n| image_seal                      = <!-- Maps -->\n| image_map                       = AKMap-doton-Atmautluak.PNG\n| mapsize                         = 250px\n| map_caption                     = Location of Kasigluk, Alaska\n| image_map1                      = \n| mapsize1                        = \n| map_caption1                    = <!-- Location -->\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = United States\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Alaska]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of boroughs and census areas in Alaska|Census Area]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Bethel Census Area, Alaska|Bethel]]\n| government_footnotes            = \n| government_type                 = \n| leader_title                    = [[Alaska Senate|State senator]]\n| leader_name                     = [[Lyman Hoffman]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D-C]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alaskasenate.org/2020/member/lyman-hoffman/ |title=Senator Lyman Hoffman |publisher=Alaskasenate.org |website=Alaska Senate Majority |access-date=November 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| leader_title1                   = [[Alaska House of Representatives|State rep.]]\n| leader_name1                    = [[Tiffany Zulkosky]] (D)\n| established_title               = \n| established_date                = <!-- Area -->\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_magnitude                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = 34.0\n| area_land_km2                   = 31.3\n| area_water_km2                  = 2.7\n| area_total_sq_mi                = \n| area_land_sq_mi                 = \n| area_water_sq_mi                = <!-- Population -->\n| population_as_of                = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_total                = 569\n| population_density_km2          = 18.2\n| population_density_sq_mi        = <!-- General information -->\n| timezone                        = [[Alaska Time Zone|Alaska (AKST)]]\n| utc_offset                      = -9\n| timezone_DST                    = AKDT\n| utc_offset_DST                  = -8\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| elevation_ft                    = \n| coordinates                     = {{coord|60|53|31|N|162|32|9|W|region:US-AK|display=inline}}\n| postal_code_type                = [[ZIP code]]\n| postal_code                     = 99609\n| area_code                       = [[Area code 907|907]]\n| blank_name                      = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info                      = 02-37975\n| blank1_name                     = \n| blank1_info                     = \n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = \n| name                            = \n}}\n[[File:Russian orthodox church in Kasigluk.jpg|thumb|Holy Trinity Russian Orthodox Church]]\n'''Kasigluk''' {{IPAc-en|k|\u0259|\u02c8|s|\u026a|\u0261|l|\u028a|k}} (''Kassigluq'' in [[Central Alaskan Yup'ik language|Yup'ik]]) is a [[census-designated place]] (CDP) in the [[Bethel Census Area, Alaska|Bethel Census Area]] in the U.S. state of [[Alaska]]. At the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]] the population was 569,<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US0237975| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212182811/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US0237975| url-status=dead| archive-date=February 12, 2020| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): Kasigluk CDP, Alaska| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> up from 543 in 2000. Kasigluk consists of two smaller villages, called Akiuk and Akula.\n\n==Geography==\nKasigluk is located at {{coord|60|53|31|N|162|32|9|W|type:city}} (60.892005, -162.535805)<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> along the Johnson River in the [[Yukon\u2013Kuskokwim Delta]] of western Alaska. It is approximately {{convert|20|mi}} northwest of [[Bethel, Alaska|Bethel]].\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the CDP has a total area of {{convert|34.0|km2|disp=flip}}, of which {{convert|31.3|km2|disp=flip}} is land and {{convert|2.7|km2|disp=flip}}, or 7.94%, is water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1940= 66\n|1950= 111\n|1960= 244\n|1990= 425\n|2000= 543\n|2010= 569\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 6, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\nKasigluk first appeared on the 1940 U.S. Census as an unincorporated native village named \"Kaseglok.\" In 1950 and 1960, it appeared as \"Kasiglook.\" In 1969, Kasigluk and a nearby village of [[Nunapitchuk, Alaska|Nunapitchuk]] merged to form the city of [[Akolmiut, Alaska|Akolmiut]]. The combined population in 1970 was 526 and in 1980 was 641. In 1982, both communities decided to dissolve Akolmiut and become separate cities again. 1990 was the first census where Kasigluk appeared with its present spelling. In 1996, Kasigluk disincorporated and was made a census-designated place effective with the 2000 census.\n\nAs of the census<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 543 people, 101 households, and 91 families residing in the CDP.  The population density was 44.5 people per square mile (17.2/km\u00b2).  There were 110 housing units at an average density of 9.0/sq&nbsp;mi (3.5/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the CDP was 3.31% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 96.50% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], and 0.18% from two or more races.  0.37% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 101 households out of which 72.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 67.3% were married couples living together, 15.8% had a female householder with no husband present, and 9.9% were non-families. 9.9% of all households were made up of individuals and 1.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 5.38 and the average family size was 5.81.\n\nIn the CDP, the population was spread out with 46.6% under the age of 18, 9.6% from 18 to 24, 26.3% from 25 to 44, 11.8% from 45 to 64, and 5.7% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 21 years. For every 100 females, there were 98.9 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 98.6 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the CDP was $31,500, and the median income for a family was $33,750. Males had a median income of $16,667 versus $18,750 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the CDP was $7,194.  About 18.9% of families and 22.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 26.7% of those under age 18 and none of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Wind power==\nRural Alaska villages have traditionally relied upon [[diesel generator]]s for their electrical needs. Kasigluk is one of several rural Alaska villages implementing [[wind power]]; they have three turbines, each with a capacity of 100 [[kilowatt]]s.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.nativeenergy.com/projects.html#8| title=Our Featured Projects| publisher=Native Energy| accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| url=http://tdworld.com/info_systems/highlights/Alaskan-Electric-Wind/| title=Alaskan Electric Cooperative Expands Wind Turbine Fleet| publisher=T&D World Magazine| date=Nov 5, 2005| accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> With fuel costs rising as high as $6 per gallon in mid-2005, wind power is being pursued not only for ecological reasons, but also to reduce the cost of living in impoverished communities such as Kasigluk.\n\n==Education==\nThe village has two schools operated by the [[Lower Kuskokwim School District]]:\n* Kasigluk-Akula Elitnaurvik School\n** The school covers PreK-12 and is a bilingual English-[[Yugtun language|Yugtun]] school. {{Asof|2018}} it has about 120 students.<ref>\"[http://akula.lksd.org/about/akula_school Akula School].\" Kasigluk-Akula Elitnaurvik School. Retrieved on July 13, 2018.</ref>\n* Kasigluk Akiuk Memorial School\n** The school covers PreK-12. {{Asof|2018}} it has about 100 students.<ref>\"[http://akiuk.lksd.org/about/akiuk_memorial_school Akiuk Memorial School].\" Kasigluk Akiuk Memorial School. Retrieved on July 13, 2018.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070311015559/http://www.lknea.org/siteinfo/akiuk.htm Lower Kuskokwim School District - Kasigluk-Akiuk]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070311015608/http://www.lknea.org/siteinfo/akula.htm Lower Kuskokwim School District - Kasigluk-Akula]\n\n{{Coord|display=title|60.892005|-162.535805}}\n{{Bethel Census Area, Alaska}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Former cities in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Bethel Census Area, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Unorganized Borough, Alaska]]\n", "name_user": "Menchi", "label": "safe", "comment": "langtags", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kasigluk,_Alaska"}
{"title_page": "Ekuk, Alaska", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement \n | official_name = Ekuk, Alaska \n | native_name = Iquk \n      | native_name_lang = esu \n | nickname = \n | image_skyline = Ekuk docks.jpg\n | image_flag =  \n | image_seal = \n | image_map = <!--Map of Alaska highlighting Ekuk.gif-->\n | map_caption = Location in the state of [[Alaska]] \n | subdivision_type =  \n | subdivision_name =  \n |leader_title             = [[Alaska Senate|State senator]]\n |leader_name              = [[Lyman Hoffman]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\n |leader_title1            = [[Alaska House of Representatives|State rep.]]\n |leader_name1             = [[Bryce Edgmon]] (D)\n | area_magnitude =  \n | area_total_km2 = \n | area_land_km2 = \n | area_water_km2 = \n |area_total_sq_mi        =4.7  \n |area_land_sq_mi         = 4.7\n |area_water_sq_mi        = 0.0\n |area_water_percent     = \n | population_as_of = 2010 \n | population_metro =  \n | population_total = 2 \n | population_density_km2 =  \n | timezone = [[Alaska Standard Time Zone|AKST]] \n | utc_offset = -9 \n | timezone_DST = [[Alaska Daylight Time|AKDT]] \n | utc_offset_DST = -8 \n | coordinates      = {{coord|58|48|12|N|158|33|34|W|type:city_region:US-AK|display=inline,title}}\n | elevation_m =  \n | website = [https://web.archive.org/web/20120204172828/http://www.dced.state.ak.us/dca/commdb/CIS.cfm?Comm_Boro_Name=Ekuk State of Alaska: Ekuk] \n | footnotes = 72 housing units\n }}\n\n'''Ekuk''' ({{lang-esu|Iquk}})<ref name=\"yupeskdict\">Jacobson, Steven A. (2012). [http://www.uaf.edu/anla/collections/search/resultDetail.xml?id=CY972J2012 Yup'ik Eskimo Dictionary, 2nd edition]. Alaska Native Language Center.</ref> is a small [[unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in the [[Dillingham Census Area, Alaska|Dillingham Census Area]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Alaska]]. As of both the 2000 and 2010 U.S. Censuses, it had a population of 2. It is classified by the U.S. Census as an Alaska Native Village Statistical Area (ANVSA). Until 2002 it was the site of a large fish processing operation owned by [[Wards Cove Packing Company]]. Currently, it is inhabited mainly by seasonal fishing families who set gillnet in the nearby waters of the Nushagak Bay for mid-summer runs of [[sockeye salmon]], early season runs of [[king salmon]] and late season runs of [[Coho salmon|silver salmon]].\n\nLocated 15 miles southeast of [[Dillingham, Alaska|Dillingham]], Ekuk is accessible only by sea or by air.\n\nLocated in Southwest Alaska on the shores of [[Bristol Bay]] (and the [[Bering Sea]]), the nearby terrain is covered with [[tundra]] with few trees or shrubbery.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1880= 112\n|1890= 65\n|1930= 37\n|1960= 40\n|1970= 51\n|1980= 7\n|1990= 3\n|2000= 2\n|2010= 2\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 6, 2013|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6YSasqtfX?url=http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archive-date=May 12, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\nEkuk first appeared on the 1880 U.S. Census as an unincorporated village of 112 residents, all Yup'ik. It appeared as \"Yekuk\" on the 1890 census. It did not appear on the census again until 1930 (as Ekuk), and then not again until 1960. It was given the census designation of Alaska Native Village Statistical Area (ANVSA) in 1990.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/dcra/DCRAExternal/community/Details=Ekuk Alaska Division of Community Advocacy - Community Information Summary] {{dead link|date=December 2015}}\n\n{{Dillingham Census Area, Alaska}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Dillingham Census Area, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Unorganized Borough, Alaska]]\n\n\n{{DillinghamAK-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement \n | official_name = Ekuk, Alaska \n | native_name = Iquk \n | nickname = \n | image_skyline = Ekuk docks.jpg\n | image_flag =  \n | image_seal = \n | image_map = <!--Map of Alaska highlighting Ekuk.gif-->\n | map_caption = Location in the state of [[Alaska]] \n | subdivision_type =  \n | subdivision_name =  \n |leader_title             = [[Alaska Senate|State senator]]\n |leader_name              = [[Lyman Hoffman]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\n |leader_title1            = [[Alaska House of Representatives|State rep.]]\n |leader_name1             = [[Bryce Edgmon]] (D)\n | area_magnitude =  \n | area_total_km2 = \n | area_land_km2 = \n | area_water_km2 = \n |area_total_sq_mi        =4.7  \n |area_land_sq_mi         = 4.7\n |area_water_sq_mi        = 0.0\n |area_water_percent     = \n | population_as_of = 2010 \n | population_metro =  \n | population_total = 2 \n | population_density_km2 =  \n | timezone = [[Alaska Standard Time Zone|AKST]] \n | utc_offset = -9 \n | timezone_DST = [[Alaska Daylight Time|AKDT]] \n | utc_offset_DST = -8 \n | coordinates      = {{coord|58|48|12|N|158|33|34|W|type:city_region:US-AK|display=inline,title}}\n | elevation_m =  \n | website = [https://web.archive.org/web/20120204172828/http://www.dced.state.ak.us/dca/commdb/CIS.cfm?Comm_Boro_Name=Ekuk State of Alaska: Ekuk] \n | footnotes = 72 housing units\n }}\n\n'''Ekuk''' ([[Central Alaskan Yup'ik language|Yup'ik]] ''Iquk''<ref name=\"yupeskdict\">Jacobson, Steven A. (2012). [http://www.uaf.edu/anla/collections/search/resultDetail.xml?id=CY972J2012 Yup'ik Eskimo Dictionary, 2nd edition]. Alaska Native Language Center.</ref>) is a small [[unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in the [[Dillingham Census Area, Alaska|Dillingham Census Area]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Alaska]]. As of both the 2000 and 2010 U.S. Censuses, it had a population of 2. It is classified by the U.S. Census as an Alaska Native Village Statistical Area (ANVSA). Until 2002 it was the site of a large fish processing operation owned by [[Wards Cove Packing Company]]. Currently, it is inhabited mainly by seasonal fishing families who set gillnet in the nearby waters of the Nushagak Bay for mid-summer runs of [[sockeye salmon]], early season runs of [[king salmon]] and late season runs of [[Coho salmon|silver salmon]].\n\nLocated 15 miles southeast of [[Dillingham, Alaska|Dillingham]], Ekuk is accessible only by sea or by air.\n\nLocated in Southwest Alaska on the shores of [[Bristol Bay]] (and the [[Bering Sea]]), the nearby terrain is covered with [[tundra]] with few trees or shrubbery.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1880= 112\n|1890= 65\n|1930= 37\n|1960= 40\n|1970= 51\n|1980= 7\n|1990= 3\n|2000= 2\n|2010= 2\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 6, 2013|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6YSasqtfX?url=http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archive-date=May 12, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\nEkuk first appeared on the 1880 U.S. Census as an unincorporated village of 112 residents, all Yup'ik. It appeared as \"Yekuk\" on the 1890 census. It did not appear on the census again until 1930 (as Ekuk), and then not again until 1960. It was given the census designation of Alaska Native Village Statistical Area (ANVSA) in 1990.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/dcra/DCRAExternal/community/Details=Ekuk Alaska Division of Community Advocacy - Community Information Summary] {{dead link|date=December 2015}}\n\n{{Dillingham Census Area, Alaska}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Dillingham Census Area, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Unorganized Borough, Alaska]]\n\n\n{{DillinghamAK-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Menchi", "label": "safe", "comment": "langtags", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ekuk,_Alaska"}
{"title_page": "Resistir\u00e9 (D\u00fao Din\u00e1mico song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song|name=Resistir\u00e9|cover=|alt=|type=single|artist=[[D\u00fao Din\u00e1mico]]|album=[[En Forma]]|released=[[1988 in music|1988]]|format=|recorded=|studio=|venue=|genre=[[Pop music|Pop]]|length=4:02|label=Sony|writer=[[Carlos Toro Montoro]], [[Manuel de la Calva]]|producer=|prev_title=|prev_year=|next_title=|next_year=}}\n\"'''Resistir\u00e9'''\" (English: \"I Will Resist\") is a song by the Spanish group [[D\u00fao Din\u00e1mico]] (Dynamic Duo in English), which appeared on their 1988 album ''En forma'', the second one released by the duo after their reappearence two years before with the album ''D\u00fao Din\u00e1mico'', the first one they recorded for [[Sony]].\n\nIt has become one of the most well-known songs of the group, especially after being included in the soundtrack of [[Pedro Almod\u00f3var]]'s film ''[[\u00a1\u00c1tame!]]'' (1990) and being chosen as an anthem during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain]], being played in many cities and neighborhoods of the country every day at 8 pm along with the applause that Spanish citizens dedicate every day to their health services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mundiario.com/articulo/gente/carlos-toro-montoro-periodista-deportivo-es-artifice-tema-resistire/20200329184040179889.html|title=Carlos Toro Montoro, periodista deportivo, es el art\u00edfice del tema Resistir\u00e9|last=MUNDIARIO|website=MUNDIARIO|language=es|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n''Resistir\u00e9'' was composed by Manuel de la Calva, one of the members of the Duo Din\u00e1mico, who was inspired by [[Camilo Jos\u00e9 Cela]]'s phrase \u201c''el que resiste gana''\u201d<ref name=caracas>{{cita noticia|apellidos1=AQUILINO|nombre1=JOS\u00c9 MATA|t\u00edtulo=\u201cResistir\u00e9\u201d naci\u00f3 para hacer historia|url=https://www.eluniversal.com/entretenimiento/66461/resistire\u201d-nacio-para-hacer-historia|fechaacceso=17 de abril de 2020|obra=[[El Universal (Caracas)]]|fecha=3 de abril de 2020|idioma=es|cita=\u201cEl que resiste gana\u201d. Esta frase, dicha en un programa de televisi\u00f3n por el Premio Nobel de Literatura, Camilo Jos\u00e9 Cela, inspir\u00f3 a Manolo de la Calva|urlarchivo=https://web.archive.org/web/20200417114309/https://www.eluniversal.com/entretenimiento/66461/resistire\u201d-nacio-para-hacer-historia |fechaarchivo=17 de abril de 2020}} </ref> and the lyrics were written by [[Carlos Toro Montoro]], sports journalist and Spanish composer, creator of more than 1,800 songs with many of them becoming important hits.<ref name=\"ElPais20200317\">{{Cite web|url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2020-03-17/resistire-la-vacuna-emocional-de-espana-que-urdio-un-pesimista.html|title=\u2018Resistir\u00e9\u2019, la vacuna emocional de Espa\u00f1a que urdi\u00f3 un pesimista|last=Marcos|first=Carlos|date=2020-03-17|website=EL PA\u00cdS|language=es|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== Versions ==\nOn January 13, 2003, the Argentine television station [[Telefe]] premiered the tele-novel ''[[Resistir\u00e9]]''. A version of the eponymous song was selected, performed by the singer and composer David Bolzoni -ex AQM- who participated in a casting with other versions of great Argentine artists of the stature of Antonio Birabent, La portuaria, JAF. The winner to everyone's surprise was that of the AQM duo (it was a peculiarity since the original performers were also a duo). With an eloquent and very seasoned interpretation of the singer and with a punk-rock base, this version became a success overwhelming in Argentina at a time of a deep economic crisis, reaching the hearts of millions of Argentines, and reaching the number one position in radio rankings. The version of AQM also had repercussions in other countries, where the soap opera \"Resistir\u00e9\" was also broadcast.\n\n=== Anthem of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain ===\nDuring the quarantine due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain|2020 coronavirus pandemic]], the song became popular again among the citizens, that went out to the balconies to sing it along and to encourage the workers of the Spanish Health System. It has been identified as an anthem of resistance and overcoming of the health crisis.<ref name=\"ElPais20200317\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/cultura/musica/2020/03/19/5e734a3efc6c83e73d8b467b.html|title=Letra de Resistir\u00e9, la canci\u00f3n del D\u00fao Din\u00e1mico que se ha convertido en himno del coronavirus|date=2020-03-19|website=ELMUNDO|language=es|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libertaddigital.com/cultura/musica/2020-03-18/resistire-el-himno-del-coronavirus-que-ayudo-a-manuel-de-la-calva-a-superar-un-cancer-1276654171/|title=\"Resistir\u00e9\", el himno del coronavirus que ayud\u00f3 a Manuel de la Calva a superar un c\u00e1ncer|last=Rom\u00e1n|first=Manuel|date=2020-03-18|website=Libertad Digital - Cultura|language=es-ES|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nWith this purpose, a new version was recorded featuring many well-known Spanish singers: [[\u00c1lex Ubago]], [[\u00c1lvaro Soler]], Andr\u00e9s Ceballos ([[Dvicio]]), [[Andr\u00e9s Su\u00e1rez]], [[Blas Cant\u00f3]], [[Carlos Baute]], [[Conchita]], [[David Bisbal]], [[David Otero]], [[David Summers Rodr\u00edguez|David Summers]], Dani Marco (Despistaos), [[Diana Navarro]], Ele, Georgina, [[India Mart\u00ednez]], Iv\u00e1n Torres ([[Efecto Pasillo]]), [[Jos\u00e9 Merc\u00e9]], Josemi Carmona, [[Manuel Carrasco]], [[Melendi]], [[Mikel Erentxun]], Nil Moliner, [[Pastora Soler]], [[Pedro Guerra]], Pitingo, [[Rosana Arbelo|Rosana]], [[Rozal\u00e9n]], Rulo, Sof\u00eda Ellar, Susana Alva ([[Efecto Mariposa]]) y [[Vanesa Mart\u00edn]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cope.es/tu-radio/noticias/cadena-100-reune-mas-artistas-una-nueva-version-resistire-2020-20200331_663636|title=CADENA 100 une al mundo de la m\u00fasica en 'RESISTIR\u00c9 2020', el himno para vencer juntos al coronavirus|last=Digital|first=Redacci\u00f3n|date=2020-03-31|website=COPE|language=es|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nIts authors also transferred the rights of the song to the [[Community of Madrid]], for its use in institutional campaigns while the state of alarm due to coronavirus lasts. The social repercussion caused has increased views on Spotify by more than 435% since March 15, 2020, after publications began to circulate on people's social networks singing it on their balconies, according to the EFE Agency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpais.com/espana/madrid/2020-04-01/resistire-y-pero-a-tu-lado-se-convierten-en-himnos-para-la-comunidad-de-madrid.html|title=Los autores de \u2019Resistir\u00e9\u2019 y \u2018Pero a tu lado\u2019 ceden sus derechos a la Comunidad de Madrid|last=Mart\u00ednez|first=H\u00e9ctor Llanos|date=2020-04-01|website=EL PA\u00cdS|language=es|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1988 songs]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song|name=Resistir\u00e9|cover=|alt=|type=single|artist=[[D\u00fao Din\u00e1mico]]|album=[[En Forma]]|released=[[1988 in music|1988]]|format=|recorded=|studio=|venue=|genre=[[Pop music|Pop]]|length=4:02|label=Sony|writer=[[Carlos Toro Montoro]], [[Manuel de la Calva]]|producer=|prev_title=|prev_year=|next_title=|next_year=}}\n\"'''Resistir\u00e9'''\" (English: \"I Will Resist\") is a song by the Spanish group [[D\u00fao Din\u00e1mico]] (Dynamic Duo in English), which appeared on their 1988 album ''En forma'', the second one released by the duo after their reappearence two years before with the album ''D\u00fao Din\u00e1mico'', the first one they recorded for [[Sony]].\n\nIt has become one of the most well-known songs of the group, especially after being included in the soundtrack of [[Pedro Almod\u00f3var]]'s film ''[[\u00a1\u00c1tame!]]'' (1990) and being chosen as an anthem during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain]], being played in many cities and neighborhoods of the country every day at 8 pm along with the applause that Spanish citizens dedicate every day to their health services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mundiario.com/articulo/gente/carlos-toro-montoro-periodista-deportivo-es-artifice-tema-resistire/20200329184040179889.html|title=Carlos Toro Montoro, periodista deportivo, es el art\u00edfice del tema Resistir\u00e9|last=MUNDIARIO|website=MUNDIARIO|language=es|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n\"Resistir\u00e9\" was composed by Manuel de la Calva, one of the members of the Duo Din\u00e1mico, who was inspired by [[Camilo Jos\u00e9 Cela]]'s phrase \u201c''El que resiste gana''\u201d<ref name=caracas>{{cita noticia|apellidos1=AQUILINO|nombre1=JOS\u00c9 MATA|t\u00edtulo=\u201cResistir\u00e9\u201d naci\u00f3 para hacer historia|url=https://www.eluniversal.com/entretenimiento/66461/resistire\u201d-nacio-para-hacer-historia|fechaacceso=17 de abril de 2020|obra=[[El Universal (Caracas)]]|fecha=3 de abril de 2020|idioma=es|cita=\u201cEl que resiste gana\u201d. Esta frase, dicha en un programa de televisi\u00f3n por el Premio Nobel de Literatura, Camilo Jos\u00e9 Cela, inspir\u00f3 a Manolo de la Calva|urlarchivo=https://web.archive.org/web/20200417114309/https://www.eluniversal.com/entretenimiento/66461/resistire\u201d-nacio-para-hacer-historia |fechaarchivo=17 de abril de 2020}} </ref> and the lyrics were written by [[Carlos Toro Montoro]], sports journalist and Spanish composer, creator of more than 1,800 songs with many of them becoming important hits.<ref name=\"ElPais20200317\">{{Cite web|url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2020-03-17/resistire-la-vacuna-emocional-de-espana-que-urdio-un-pesimista.html|title=\u2018Resistir\u00e9\u2019, la vacuna emocional de Espa\u00f1a que urdi\u00f3 un pesimista|last=Marcos|first=Carlos|date=2020-03-17|website=EL PA\u00cdS|language=es|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== Versions ==\nOn January 13, 2003, the Argentine television station [[Telefe]] premiered the tele-novel ''[[Resistir\u00e9]]''. A version of the eponymous song was selected, performed by the singer and composer David Bolzoni -ex AQM- who participated in a casting with other versions of great Argentine artists of the stature of Antonio Birabent, La portuaria, JAF. The winner to everyone's surprise was that of the AQM duo (it was a peculiarity since the original performers were also a duo). With an eloquent and very seasoned interpretation of the singer and with a punk-rock base, this version became a success overwhelming in Argentina at a time of a deep economic crisis, reaching the hearts of millions of Argentines, and reaching the number one position in radio rankings. The version of AQM also had repercussions in other countries, where the soap opera \"Resistir\u00e9\" was also broadcast.\n\n=== Anthem of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain ===\nDuring the quarantine due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain|2020 coronavirus pandemic]], the song became popular again among the citizens, that went out to the balconies to sing it along and to encourage the workers of the Spanish Health System. It has been identified as an anthem of resistance and overcoming of the health crisis.<ref name=\"ElPais20200317\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/cultura/musica/2020/03/19/5e734a3efc6c83e73d8b467b.html|title=Letra de Resistir\u00e9, la canci\u00f3n del D\u00fao Din\u00e1mico que se ha convertido en himno del coronavirus|date=2020-03-19|website=ELMUNDO|language=es|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libertaddigital.com/cultura/musica/2020-03-18/resistire-el-himno-del-coronavirus-que-ayudo-a-manuel-de-la-calva-a-superar-un-cancer-1276654171/|title=\"Resistir\u00e9\", el himno del coronavirus que ayud\u00f3 a Manuel de la Calva a superar un c\u00e1ncer|last=Rom\u00e1n|first=Manuel|date=2020-03-18|website=Libertad Digital - Cultura|language=es-ES|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nWith this purpose, a new version was recorded featuring many well-known Spanish singers: [[\u00c1lex Ubago]], [[\u00c1lvaro Soler]], Andr\u00e9s Ceballos ([[Dvicio]]), [[Andr\u00e9s Su\u00e1rez]], [[Blas Cant\u00f3]], [[Carlos Baute]], [[Conchita]], [[David Bisbal]], [[David Otero]], [[David Summers Rodr\u00edguez|David Summers]], Dani Marco (Despistaos), [[Diana Navarro]], Ele, Georgina, [[India Mart\u00ednez]], Iv\u00e1n Torres ([[Efecto Pasillo]]), [[Jos\u00e9 Merc\u00e9]], Josemi Carmona, [[Manuel Carrasco]], [[Melendi]], [[Mikel Erentxun]], Nil Moliner, [[Pastora Soler]], [[Pedro Guerra]], Pitingo, [[Rosana Arbelo|Rosana]], [[Rozal\u00e9n]], Rulo, Sof\u00eda Ellar, Susana Alva ([[Efecto Mariposa]]) y [[Vanesa Mart\u00edn]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cope.es/tu-radio/noticias/cadena-100-reune-mas-artistas-una-nueva-version-resistire-2020-20200331_663636|title=CADENA 100 une al mundo de la m\u00fasica en 'RESISTIR\u00c9 2020', el himno para vencer juntos al coronavirus|last=Digital|first=Redacci\u00f3n|date=2020-03-31|website=COPE|language=es|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nIts authors also transferred the rights of the song to the [[Community of Madrid]], for its use in institutional campaigns while the state of alarm due to coronavirus lasts. The social repercussion caused has increased views on Spotify by more than 435% since March 15, 2020, after publications began to circulate on people's social networks singing it on their balconies, according to the EFE Agency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpais.com/espana/madrid/2020-04-01/resistire-y-pero-a-tu-lado-se-convierten-en-himnos-para-la-comunidad-de-madrid.html|title=Los autores de \u2019Resistir\u00e9\u2019 y \u2018Pero a tu lado\u2019 ceden sus derechos a la Comunidad de Madrid|last=Mart\u00ednez|first=H\u00e9ctor Llanos|date=2020-04-01|website=EL PA\u00cdS|language=es|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1988 songs]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain]]\n", "name_user": "XavierItzm", "label": "safe", "comment": "style", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resistir%C3%A9_(D%C3%BAo_Din%C3%A1mico_song)"}
